    </tools>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>EU AI Act Compliance</title>

    <summary>The EU AI Act imposes fines up to EUR 35M or 7% of global turnover for non-compliance. Risk classification determines which articles apply; incorrect classification — either under- or over-scoping — leads to either regulatory exposure or unnecessary engineering cost. Agents producing compliance drafts must cite specific articles and flag ambiguous cases for legal review.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>The EU AI Act imposes fines up to EUR 35M or 7% of global turnover for non-compliance. Risk classification determines which articles apply; incorrect classification — either under- or over-scoping — leads to either regulatory exposure or unnecessary engineering cost. Agents producing compliance drafts must cite specific articles and flag ambiguous cases for legal review.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Building or deploying an AI system targeting EU users after August 2024</item>
        <item>Any system processing biometrics, employment decisions, credit scoring, education admissions, or critical infrastructure — all are Annex III high-risk</item>
        <item>Deploying a GPAI model (General Purpose AI) with &gt;10^25 FLOPs training compute (systemic risk tier, Aug 2025 deadline)</item>
        <item>Integrating third-party LLM APIs where the provider's compliance does not cover downstream deployer obligations</item>
        <item>Conducting a pre-launch compliance gap analysis</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Products deployed exclusively outside the EU with no EU users or EU-based processing</item>
        <item>Purely internal tools with no impact on individuals' rights or safety (minimal risk tier — no obligations)</item>
        <item>R&amp;D activities exempt under Article 2(6) — lab testing does not require compliance</item>
        <item>Open-source models released without commercial intent may have reduced obligations (verify per Article 2(12))</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="risk-tiers">
      <p>Four-tier risk framework where risk tier determines which articles apply, documentation depth, and conformity assessment path.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Classify every AI system before any architectural decision; retrofitting compliance is more costly than designing for it.</statement>
        <rationale>Risk tier determines which articles apply, documentation depth, and conformity assessment path.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Tiers in descending severity: Unacceptable (prohibited) → High → Limited → Minimal.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="prohibited-practices">
      <p>Prohibited practices under Article 5 are absolute — no proportionality test applies. Violations carry EUR 35M or 7% turnover fines.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Do not deploy any system matching a prohibited practice regardless of claimed benefit.</statement>
        <rationale>Article 5 is absolute — no proportionality test applies. Violations carry EUR 35M or 7% turnover fines.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Subliminal manipulation of behavior below conscious awareness</item>
        <item>Exploitation of vulnerabilities of specific groups (age, disability)</item>
        <item>Social scoring by public authorities</item>
        <item>Real-time remote biometric identification in public spaces (narrow law-enforcement exceptions)</item>
        <item>Predictive policing based solely on profiling</item>
        <item>Emotion recognition in workplace or educational settings</item>
        <item>Untargeted facial recognition database scraping</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="high-risk-domains">
      <p>Annex III enumerates eight domains where AI decisions can adversely affect fundamental rights. If the system's primary purpose maps to any of these, treat it as high-risk and apply Articles 9–15, 17, 43.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>If the system's primary purpose maps to any Annex III domain, treat it as high-risk and apply Articles 9–15, 17, 43.</statement>
        <rationale>Annex III enumerates eight domains where AI decisions can adversely affect fundamental rights.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Biometrics — remote identification, categorization, emotion recognition</item>
        <item>Critical infrastructure — energy, transport, water, digital</item>
        <item>Education — admissions, assessment, proctoring, dropout prediction</item>
        <item>Employment — recruitment, performance evaluation, promotion, termination</item>
        <item>Essential services — credit scoring, insurance, emergency dispatch</item>
        <item>Law enforcement — risk assessment, lie detection, crime prediction</item>
        <item>Migration — visa, asylum, border control</item>
        <item>Justice — legal research, dispute resolution, judicial decisions</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="limited-risk-disclosure">
      <p>For chatbots, synthetic content generators, emotion recognition, and biometric categorization: disclose AI involvement clearly and timely.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For chatbots, synthetic content generators, emotion recognition, and biometric categorization: disclose AI involvement clearly and timely.</statement>
        <rationale>Article 50 requires transparency where users may assume human interaction or be misled about AI-generated content.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="gpai-obligations">
      <p>General Purpose AI (GPAI) models above the systemic risk threshold must publish model cards and training data summaries by August 2025; models above 10^25 FLOPs training compute must also conduct red-teaming and report serious incidents.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>GPAI providers must publish model cards and training data summaries by August 2025; models above 10^25 FLOPs training compute must also conduct red-teaming and report serious incidents.</statement>
        <rationale>Systemic risk threshold targets foundation models with broad societal impact.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="penalties">
      <list>
        <item>Prohibited AI deployment: EUR 35M or 7% global annual turnover (whichever higher)</item>
        <item>High-risk non-compliance: EUR 15M or 3% global turnover</item>
        <item>Other violations / false information: EUR 7.5M or 1% global turnover</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="enforcement-timeline">
      <list>
        <item>Feb 2025: Prohibited practices ban in force; AI literacy obligations begin</item>
        <item>Aug 2025: GPAI model compliance (transparency, copyright, documentation)</item>
        <item>Aug 2026: Full high-risk AI system compliance; Article 50 transparency</item>
        <item>Aug 2027: Extended transition for high-risk AI in CE-marked regulated products</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="compliance-phases">
      <p>Phased compliance checklist: GPAI obligations (Aug 2025), high-risk system requirements (Aug 2026), and deployer duties.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Prepare technical documentation, model cards, and training data summaries before August 2025 for all GPAI models.</statement>
        <rationale>GPAI obligations are the first hard deadline after the prohibited-practices ban.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Phase 1 — GPAI Models (August 2025):</p>
      <list>
        <item>Prepare technical documentation for GPAI models including capabilities and limitations</item>
        <item>Create model cards with architecture, training methodology, and evaluation results</item>
        <item>Document training data sources, types, and preprocessing</item>
        <item>Implement copyright compliance (respect robots.txt, opt-out mechanisms)</item>
        <item>For systemic risk (&gt;10^25 FLOPs): red-team, assess systemic risks, track incidents</item>
      </list>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>High-risk AI providers must implement all seven Article requirements and register in the EU AI database before deployment.</statement>
        <rationale>Article 9–17 requirements are cumulative; incomplete implementation invalidates conformity assessment.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Phase 2 — High-Risk Providers (August 2026):</p>
      <list>
        <item>Article 9: Risk management system — identify, estimate, mitigate, test residual risks</item>
        <item>Article 10: Data governance — document training data, verify quality, address bias</item>
        <item>Article 11: Technical documentation — system description, design specs, test results</item>
        <item>Article 12: Record-keeping — automatic logging, traceable events, defined retention</item>
        <item>Article 13: Transparency — instructions for use, capabilities, limitations disclosed</item>
        <item>Article 14: Human oversight — override capability designed in, not bolted on</item>
        <item>Article 15: Accuracy, robustness, cybersecurity — adversarial attack mitigations</item>
        <item>Article 17: Quality management system — compliance strategy, corrective actions</item>
        <item>Article 43: Conformity assessment — self-assessment or third-party per category</item>
        <item>Article 71: EU database registration before deployment</item>
      </list>

      <p>Phase 2 — Deployers of High-Risk Systems:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Verify provider compliance documentation before integration</item>
        <item>Implement human oversight measures as specified in provider instructions</item>
        <item>Monitor AI system operation and report malfunctions to provider</item>
        <item>Conduct fundamental rights impact assessment (where required by sector)</item>
        <item>Inform workers and affected individuals of AI use</item>
      </list>

      <p>Limited Risk — Article 50 Transparency:</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Chatbots must disclose AI nature at conversation start; AI-generated images/video must carry machine-readable watermarks.</statement>
        <rationale>Users have the right to know when interacting with AI; content authenticity enables fact-checking.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Chatbots: Disclose AI nature clearly at first interaction; offer human escalation</item>
        <item>Synthetic content: Add C2PA-compatible machine-readable watermarks</item>
        <item>Emotion recognition: Inform subjects; obtain consent; comply with GDPR</item>
      </list>

      <p>Ongoing Compliance:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Track AI system performance and monitor for drift or degradation</item>
        <item>Maintain and update technical documentation with every model change</item>
        <item>Establish incident reporting process with defined severity thresholds</item>
        <item>Report serious incidents to national authorities within required timelines</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="implementation-examples">
      <p>Code examples demonstrating compliance implementation for different risk tiers.</p>

      <example type="good" title="Limited Risk — Chatbot Disclosure (Article 50)">
        <p>Disclose AI nature at conversation start; provide human escalation trigger.</p>
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
class ChatbotService:
    DISCLOSURE_MESSAGE = (
        "You are chatting with an AI assistant. "
        "Type 'human' at any time to speak with a person."
    )

    def start_conversation(self, user_id: str) -> dict:
        return {
            "type": "disclosure",
            "message": self.DISCLOSURE_MESSAGE,
            "user_acknowledged": False,
        }

    def process_message(self, user_id: str, message: str) -> dict:
        if message.lower() == "human":
            return self._escalate_to_human(user_id)
        return self._generate_response(message)
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="High Risk — Resume Screener (Annex III Employment)">
        <p>Article 12 logging, Article 10 bias detection, Article 14 human-review threshold, Article 13 explainability.</p>
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from dataclasses import dataclass
from datetime import datetime

@dataclass
class CandidateEvaluation:
    candidate_id: str
    score: float
    confidence: float
    explanation: str
    bias_metrics: dict
    human_review_required: bool
    timestamp: datetime

class ResumeScreener:
    def evaluate(self, resume: dict, job_req: dict) -> CandidateEvaluation:
        self.logger.log_input(resume, job_req)           # Article 12
        risk = self.risk_manager.assess(resume)          # Article 9
        if risk.requires_intervention:
            return self._flag_for_human_review(resume, risk)

        score, features, confidence = self._score_resume(resume, job_req)
        bias = self.bias_detector.analyze(              # Article 10
            score=score,
            features=features,
            protected_attributes=["gender", "age", "ethnicity"],
        )
        human_review = confidence < 0.7 or bias["disparity_score"] > 0.1  # Art 14
        explanation = self._generate_explanation(features)                  # Art 13

        eval_ = CandidateEvaluation(
            candidate_id=resume["id"],
            score=score, confidence=confidence,
            explanation=explanation, bias_metrics=bias,
            human_review_required=human_review,
            timestamp=datetime.utcnow(),
        )
        self.logger.log_output(eval_)
        return eval_
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Limited Risk — Synthetic Content Labeling (Article 50.4)">
        <p>Add C2PA machine-readable watermark to AI-generated images.</p>
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
class SyntheticContentLabeler:
    def label_image(self, image, metadata: dict):
        return self._add_c2pa_manifest(image, {
            "ai_generated": True,
            "generator": metadata.get("model"),
            "timestamp": datetime.utcnow().isoformat(),
            "organization": metadata.get("org"),
        })

    def label_text(self, text: str, metadata: dict) -> dict:
        import hashlib
        return {
            "content": text,
            "metadata": {
                "ai_generated": True,
                "model": metadata.get("model"),
                "timestamp": datetime.utcnow().isoformat(),
                "hash": hashlib.sha256(text.encode()).hexdigest(),
            },
        }
]]></code>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Hidden AI use — responding to customer without disclosing AI.</description>
        <reason>Article 50 violation. Users interacting with AI must be informed at the earliest opportunity.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Silent emotion detection on audio/video without user consent.</description>
        <reason>Emotion recognition in workplace or education settings is prohibited under Article 5 without explicit consent and lawful basis.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Fully automated rejection of employment applications without human review.</description>
        <reason>Article 14 requires human oversight capability in high-risk systems; automated rejection with no override path violates the requirement.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

